<tt>Thu Nov 13 17:03:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
ANOTHER EXAMPLE OF AN 'EXTREMIST'MARINE<br><br>
Marine urges crowd to share the memories, horrors of war<br><br>
By Marlowe Churchill<br>
The Press-Enterprise<br>
Published 11/12/1997<br>
RIVERSIDE<br><br>
With rifle fire in the background, Vernon Pendergrass hunkered down in a bunker on the demilitarized zone in South Vietnam 30 years ago and tape recorded a message that moved many to tears Tuesday during a Veterans Day observance.<br><br>
&quot;This is what makes me homesick,&quot; he said in his Alabama drawl as he pulled out a picture of his 3-month-old daughter, Deisha, and wife, Jackie. &quot;I can hardly stand to look at my wife and baby's picture.&quot;<br><br>
K. R. &quot;Zack&quot; Earp, the U.S. Marine who included Pendergrass' comments in his taped Christmas message for his parents in Colton, re-played the message Tuesday for a crowd of more than 2,500 at the Riverside National Cemetery.<br><br>
Listening in the crowd was Deisha, a Birmingham social worker who never heard her father's voice until a reunion with Earp last year in which he resurrected the long forgotten tape of a buddy killed in combat.<br><br>
&quot;This is Deisha, man!&quot; Pendergrass shouts to Earp over the racket of gunfire.<br><br>
Tears welled in Earp's eyes as he heard again the voice of a friend.<br><br>
&quot;I wanted to share with you the ultimate sacrifice that has touched not only me, the family of my buddy, but thousands of others, too,&quot; Earp said, choking back tears.<br><br>
The two combat-tested Marines, Earp recounted, had struck up a quick and close friendship with Earp amused by Pendergrass' constant chatter and the bravado he displayed.<br><br>
&quot;He wasn't supposed to die,&quot; Earp said of the ambush that killed Pendergrass three months later.<br><br>
Earp recounted the events at one of several Inland area events to honor veterans. About 300 people attended ceremonies at Jennie Davis Memorial Park in Redlands and 200 at Fleming Park in Colton. Thirty veterans were honored at events at Heritage Mobile Home Estates in Temecula and five at The Colony in Murrieta.<br><br>
The memory of Pendergrass was captured in a few snapshots for his daughter as she grew up. Deisha said after the ceremony that her mother, who remarried briefly and still mourns Pendergrass, rarely talked about her father until Deisha pressed the issue two years ago and contacted a service organization, Sons and Daughters in Touch, that led her to Earp.<br><br>
At a Fathers Day reunion at the Vietnam War Memorial this summer, Earp and Deisha found Pendergrass' name etched in the wall and there he played the tape for her. Since then, Deisha said she has played the message over and over until she has it memorized.<br><br>
Earp has become a surrogate father, she said, and will give her away at her wedding next year.<br><br>
Earp, Alvord school board president and a former educator, told the crowd that old war wounds can only be healed by confronting and understanding the horrors veterans are trying to forget. Wounded by a land mine shortly after Pendergrass' death, Earp said his life has changed for the better since meeting Deisha.<br><br>
&quot;If you have experienced a traumatic event in combat, please, please share that with the family members of those you saw die. There are thousands of kids like Deisha,&quot; Earp said.<br><br>

